<subSubSection id="E9AF48D2BF51FF911D95F9269B8AF80B" pageId="12" pageNumber="263" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="A10A1B59BF51FF911D95F9269B8AF80B" blockId="12.[151,1437,151,2013]" pageId="12" pageNumber="263">
<emphasis id="93C1C74BBF51FF911D95F92699F8F922" bold="true" box="[199,462,1698,1724]" pageId="12" pageNumber="263">Differential diagnosis.</emphasis>
Based on the presence of six dorsal striae and a submarginal stria on each elytron, the new species can be classified within 
<taxonomicName id="66B560DABF51FF911F7FF9439AD3F97E" authorityName="Regimbart" authorityYear="1899" box="[557,741,1735,1761]" class="Insecta" family="Dytiscidae" genus="Copelatus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="263" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="irinus">
<emphasis id="93C1C74BBF51FF911F7FF9439AD3F97E" box="[557,741,1735,1761]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="263">Copelatus irinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species group. Elongate habitus, complete elytral striation and male median lobe without distinct process place 
<taxonomicName id="66B560DABF51FF911F92F96F9BACF89B" authority="Jiang &amp; Zhao &amp; Yang &amp; Jia &amp; Hájek, 2022" authorityName="Jiang &amp; Zhao &amp; Yang &amp; Jia &amp; Hájek" authorityYear="2022" box="[704,922,1771,1797]" class="Insecta" family="Dytiscidae" genus="Copelatus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="263" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mopanshanensis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="93C1C74BBF51FF911F92F96F9BACF89B" box="[704,922,1771,1797]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="263">C. mopanshanensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="88F27A30BF51FF911EF1F96F9BCCF89B" box="[931,1018,1771,1797]" pageId="12" pageNumber="263" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
in the 
<taxonomicName id="66B560DABF51FF911918F96F9CEFF89A" authorityName="Sharp" authorityYear="1884" box="[1098,1241,1771,1797]" class="Insecta" family="Dytiscidae" genus="Copelatus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="263" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="japonicus">
<emphasis id="93C1C74BBF51FF911918F96F9CEFF89A" box="[1098,1241,1771,1797]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="263">C. japonicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
complex. Within the complex, the new species can be undoubtedly recognised only based on the shape of male genitalia: median lobe is broad in basal two thirds; apical part is slenderer, bisinuous. The most similar genitalia are those of 
<taxonomicName id="66B560DABF51FF911879F8B798ECF8EF" authority="Jiang &amp; Zhao &amp; Yang &amp; Jia &amp; Hájek, 2022" authorityName="Jiang &amp; Zhao &amp; Yang &amp; Jia &amp; Hájek" authorityYear="2022" class="Insecta" family="Dytiscidae" genus="Copelatus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="263" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="felicis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="93C1C74BBF51FF911879F8B798ECF8EF" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="263">Copelatus felicis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="88F27A30BF51FF911DB2F8D3990EF8EF" box="[224,312,1879,1905]" pageId="12" pageNumber="263" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, but the median lobe is broader and with distinct swelling on ventral side in three fourths of its length, and the apical part is slenderer in the latter species (see 
<figureCitation id="398E07DCBF51FF911E54F8FF9B6FF80B" box="[774,857,1914,1941]" captionStart="FIGURES 29–38" captionStartId="38.[151,264,1819,1843]" captionTargetBox="[204,1387,192,1774]" captionTargetId="figure-23@38.[190,1398,181,1795]" captionTargetPageId="38" captionText="FIGURES 29–38. Male genitalia of Copelatus. 29, 31, 33, 35, 37. median lobe in lateral view; 30, 32, 34, 36, 38. paramere. 29–30. C. bacchusi (Hainan); 31. C. chinensis (a. Lakeshan, Zhejiang; b. Yanjiajie, Hunan; c. Tainmushan, Zhejiang); 32. C. chinensis (Tianmushan, Zhejiang); 33. C. dentatipenis sp. nov. (a. holotype, Jinggangshan, Jiangxi; b. Guadun, Fujian; c. Mangshan, Hunan); 34. C. dentatipenis sp. nov. (holotype, Jinggangshan, Jiangxi); 35–36. C. felicis sp. nov. (holotype, Baishui, Yunnan); 37. C. diversistriatus sp. nov. (a. holotype, Pu’er, Yunnan; aa. detail of lateral carina with spines; b. Attapeu, Laos; c. NE Mintaingbin Forest Camp, Myanmar); 38. C. diversistriatus sp. nov. (holotype, Pu’er, Yunnan). Scale bar 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6411116" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6411116/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="263">Figs 35</figureCitation>
and 
<figureCitation id="398E07DCBF51FF911EC2F8FE9B86F80B" box="[912,944,1914,1941]" captionStart="FIGURES 39–50" captionStartId="39.[151,264,1839,1863]" captionTargetBox="[210,1370,207,1804]" captionTargetId="figure-18@39.[192,1395,181,1815]" captionTargetPageId="39" captionText="FIGURES 39–50. Male genitalia of Copelatus. 39, 41, 43, 45, 47, 49. median lobe in lateral view; 40, 42, 44, 46, 48, 50. paramere. 39–40. C. japonicus (Shanghai); 41. C. malaisei (a. Gaoligongshan, Yunnan; b. Renjiafen, Yunnan); 42. C. malaisei (Renjiafen, Yunnan); 43–44. C. miaowangi sp. nov. (paratype, Liupanshui, Guizhou); 45–46. C. mopanshanensis sp. nov. (holotype, Mopanshan, Yunnan); 47–48. C. nanlingensis sp. nov. (holotype, Dadongshan, Guangdong); 49–50. C. oblitus (Macao). Scale bar 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6412781" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6412781/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="263">45</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="E9AF48D2BF51FF911D95F81B9A5FF843" pageId="12" pageNumber="263" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="A10A1B59BF51FF911D95F81B9A5FF843" blockId="12.[151,1437,151,2013]" pageId="12" pageNumber="263">
<emphasis id="93C1C74BBF51FF911D95F81B9978F827" bold="true" box="[199,334,1951,1977]" pageId="12" pageNumber="263">Etymology.</emphasis>
The species is named after the Mopan 
<collectingRegion id="6371D5BBBF51FF911E53F81B9B0FF827" box="[769,825,1951,1977]" country="Myanmar" name="Shan" pageId="12" pageNumber="263">Shan</collectingRegion>
mountains where it was collected. The specific epithet is an adjective in the nominative singular.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="E9AF48D2BF50FF901D95FF129A71FF4B" pageId="13" pageNumber="264" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="A10A1B59BF50FF901D95FF129A71FF4B" blockId="13.[151,1436,150,213]" pageId="13" pageNumber="264">
<emphasis id="93C1C74BBF50FF901D95FF129957FF2E" bold="true" box="[199,353,150,176]" pageId="13" pageNumber="264">Distribution.</emphasis>
A species endemic to 
<collectingCountry id="D9A25BC9BF50FF901F36FF139A9CFF2F" box="[612,682,151,177]" name="China" pageId="13" pageNumber="264">China</collectingCountry>
, so far known only from two very close localities in Mopan Shan mountains in central 
<collectingRegion id="6371D5BBBF50FF901CD0FF3F99EEFF4B" box="[386,472,187,213]" country="China" name="Yunnan" pageId="13" pageNumber="264">Yunnan</collectingRegion>
(
<figureCitation id="398E07DCBF50FF901CB5FF3F9A0DFF4B" box="[487,571,187,213]" captionStart="FIGURE 82" captionStartId="44.[151,250,1078,1102]" captionTargetBox="[265,1326,188,1049]" captionTargetId="figure-23@44.[258,1330,181,1054]" captionTargetPageId="44" captionText="FIGURE 82. Map of distribution of Copelatus in China Mainland." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6410810" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6410810/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="264">Fig. 82</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
